            p.footnote.
                #[sup ‡]Data from an eating disorder–assessed subsample (n=2,980) of the National Comorbidity Survey Replication, a nationally representative face-to-face household survey of English-speaking adults aged ≥18 and older.#[sup 1]

    section.section--
        .wrap--content

            h1.
                Onset of !{BED} occurs at a later age (21 years) than bulimia nervosa (18 years) and anorexia nervosa (18 years)#[sup §1]

            p.footnote.
                #[sup §]Data from an eating disorder–assessed subsample (n=2,980) of the National Comorbidity Survey Replication, a nationally representative face-to-face household survey of English-speaking adults aged ≥18 and older.#[sup 1]

    section.section--
        .wrap--content

            h1.
                In US adults, !{BED} is observed across racial and ethnic groups: Prevalence rates are comparable among non-Latino white (1.4%), Latino (2.1%), Asian (1.2%), and African American (1.5%) adults#[sup ¶5,6]

            h2.
                Prevalence rates are also comparable between most industrialized countries (eg, Australia, Canada, many European countries, New Zealand, and the United States)#[sup 5]

